{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01TohdMCiDx9UAmLWZ8Vzg5a","type":"tool_result","content":"     1â†’# Specification: 004 Shared Infrastructure\n     2â†’\n     3â†’## Meta\n     4â†’\n     5â†’| Field | Value |\n     6â†’|-------|-------|\n     7â†’| Status | Ready |\n     8â†’| Priority | P0 |\n     9â†’| Phase | 1 |\n    10â†’| NR_OF_TRIES | 5 |\n    11â†’\n    12â†’---\n    13â†’\n    14â†’## Overview\n    15â†’\n    16â†’Shared Infrastructure defines the common Rust crate (`solana/shared/`) that all game programs depend on. It provides escrow helpers, a standardized lifecycle state machine, timeout/refund logic, pause controls, a commit-reveal verifier, fee distribution, and platform CPI helpers. Every game compiles against this crate â€” consistency is enforced at compile time, not via CPI at runtime.\n    17â†’\n    18â†’This spec formalizes the architecture approved in the pivot doc (`docs/pivot-doc.md`) and blocks all game implementations.\n    19â†’\n    20â†’## User Stories\n    21â†’\n    22â†’- As a game developer, I want a shared lifecycle state machine so that every game follows the same round phases and invariants without reimplementation.\n    23â†’- As a player, I want timeout refunds to be permissionless so that my funds are never stuck in an unresolved round.\n    24â†’- As an auditor, I want fee math in a single crate so that I audit money-handling once and trust it everywhere.\n    25â†’- As an operator, I want global and per-game pause controls so that I can halt new rounds without blocking in-progress settlements.\n    26â†’\n    27â†’---\n    28â†’\n    29â†’## Scope Alignment\n    30â†’\n    31â†’- **`docs/SCOPE.md` references**: Section 3 (Architecture Direction), Section 4 (Source of Truth), Section 6 (Functional Requirements - on-chain settlement)\n    32â†’- **Scope status**: V1 In Scope\n    33â†’- **Phase boundary**: Phase 1 (blocks Coinflip rewrite and all subsequent games)\n    34â†’\n    35â†’## Required Context Files\n    36â†’\n    37â†’- `docs/pivot-doc.md` (Architecture Decision â€” canonical source for this spec)\n    38â†’- `docs/FOUNDATIONS.md` Â§2 (On-Chain Dev Loop), Â§5 (Randomness Strategy), Â§8 (Fee Math)\n    39â†’- `docs/SCOPE.md` (scope boundary)\n    40â†’- `solana/shared/` (existing crate â€” partial implementation)\n    41â†’\n    42â†’## Contract Files\n    43â†’\n    44â†’- `solana/shared/src/lib.rs` â€” crate root (existing)\n    45â†’- `solana/shared/src/fees.rs` â€” fee calculation (existing, to be formalized)\n    46â†’- `solana/shared/src/tiers.rs` â€” tier definitions (existing)\n    47â†’- `solana/shared/src/constants.rs` â€” constants (existing)\n    48â†’- `solana/shared/src/lifecycle.rs` â€” lifecycle state machine (to be created)\n    49â†’- `solana/shared/src/escrow.rs` â€” escrow helpers (to be created)\n    50â†’- `solana/shared/src/timeout.rs` â€” timeout logic (to be created)\n    51â†’- `solana/shared/src/pause.rs` â€” pause controls (to be created)\n    52â†’- `solana/shared/src/commit_reveal.rs` â€” commit-reveal verifier (to be created)\n    53â†’- `solana/shared/src/cpi.rs` â€” platform CPI helpers (to be created)\n    54â†’- `solana/shared/src/vrf_orao.rs` â€” Orao request/callback helpers (to be created)\n    55â†’\n    56â†’---\n    57â†’\n    58â†’## Functional Requirements\n    59â†’\n    60â†’### FR-1: Shared Crate â€” Escrow Helpers (Claim-Based Payout)\n    61â†’\n    62â†’Reusable functions for depositing SOL to a round PDA and letting participants claim their funds. Uses a **claim-based payout pattern**: for VRF games, the `claim_payout` instruction reads the VRF result at claim time (no separate settle tx), derives the winner, and transfers funds â€” all in one tx. For commit-reveal games, the server's reveal instruction writes the outcome, then players claim. Either way, the claim instruction is what moves funds.\n    63â†’\n    64â†’**Three-transaction flow for VRF games (e.g., coinflip):**\n    65â†’1. `create_match` â€” creator deposits SOL, phase = WAITING\n    66â†’2. `join_match` â€” opponent deposits SOL, requests Orao VRF, phase = LOCKED, `resolve_deadline` set\n    67â†’3. `claim_payout` â€” either player calls. Reads fulfilled Orao randomness account, derives winner, transfers payout + fee, emits audit event, closes match.\n    68â†’\n    69â†’Frontend reads the Orao randomness PDA (free, no tx) to show the result. The claim tx is what settles on-chain.\n    70â†’\n    71â†’**Acceptance Criteria:**\n    72â†’- [ ] `deposit_to_escrow(from, round_pda, amount)` transfers SOL from player to round PDA via system program CPI\n    73â†’- [ ] `claim_payout` reads VRF result at claim time (for VRF games) or reads stored outcome (for commit-reveal games), derives winner, transfers payout\n    74â†’- [ ] Either participant can trigger claim â€” payout always goes to the derived winner regardless of caller\n    75â†’- [ ] Claim is idempotent â€” double-claim returns error, does not double-pay\n    76â†’- [ ] Claim emits an Anchor event with VRF randomness bytes, derived winner, and payout amounts (audit trail â€” match PDA is closed after claim)\n    77â†’- [ ] `refund(round_pda, caller)` â€” each depositor calls individually to pull their refund after timeout\n    78â†’- [ ] `close_round(round_pda, rent_recipient)` closes the PDA and returns rent\n    79â†’- [ ] No escrow function touches fee math (fees handled separately in FR-3)\n    80â†’- [ ] **Claimable games query**: match PDAs in LOCKED phase (VRF fulfilled) or SETTLED phase (commit-reveal settled) with `claimed == false` are discoverable via `getProgramAccounts` filter by player pubkey + phase. Frontend must maintain a \"claimable / unresolved games\" list per user.\n    81â†’\n    82â†’### FR-2: Commit-Reveal Verifier\n    83â†’\n    84â†’Self-built module (~50 lines Rust) for server result verification. The server commits a hash before/at round start, then reveals the seed at settlement. The contract verifies the commitment.\n    85â†’\n    86â†’**Acceptance Criteria:**\n    87â†’- [ ] `store_commitment(round_pda, hash)` stores `SHA256(server_seed)` in the round PDA\n    88â†’- [ ] `verify_reveal(round_pda, server_seed)` checks `SHA256(server_seed) == stored_hash`\n    89â†’- [ ] Verification failure returns a typed error (commitment mismatch)\n    90â†’- [ ] On verification failure, round transitions to REFUNDED (not SETTLED)\n    91â†’- [ ] No third-party dependency â€” uses `solana_program::hash::hashv` or equivalent\n    92â†’- [ ] Module is independently testable (unit tests with known hash pairs)\n    93â†’\n    94â†’### FR-3: Fee Distribution\n    95â†’\n    96â†’Formalize existing fee math as the single path for all fee calculations. No game ever implements its own fee logic.\n    97â†’\n    98â†’**Acceptance Criteria:**\n    99â†’- [ ] `calculate_fee(pool_lamports) -> (fee, net_payout)` returns fee and payout amounts\n   100â†’- [ ] Fee = 300 bps (3%) of pool, hardcoded constant\n   101â†’- [ ] `transfer_fee(round_pda, treasury_pda, fee_amount)` sends fee to treasury\n   102â†’- [ ] Integer math only (basis points, lamports) â€” no floats\n   103â†’- [ ] Rounding favors the player (fee rounds down)\n   104â†’- [ ] `MAX_FEE_BPS = 1000` compile-time safety cap preserved\n   105â†’- [ ] Fee split (200 bps revenue, 70 bps rakeback, 30 bps chest) tracked but single treasury transfer for V1\n   106â†’\n   107â†’### FR-4: VRF Provider Integration (Orao)\n   108â†’\n   109â†’Integrate **Orao** as the single VRF provider for all games requiring randomness. Uses `orao-solana-vrf` (standard crate, not callback variant). No separate consume/resolve instruction â€” VRF result is read at claim time.\n   110â†’\n   111â†’**Integration Contract (Authoritative Shape):**\n   112â†’\n   113â†’- **Request path**: VRF is requested as part of an existing game instruction (e.g., `join_match` for coinflip). No separate `request_vrf` instruction.\n   114â†’- **Request side effects**:\n   115â†’  - CPIs into Orao to request randomness with a unique seed (derived from match PDA or round ID).\n   116â†’  - Stores `vrf_request_key` on the round account for later lookup.\n   117â†’  - Sets `resolve_deadline` for timeout safety.\n   118â†’  - Moves phase to `Locked`.\n   119â†’- **Read-at-claim path**: No separate consume/callback instruction. The `claim_payout` instruction reads the fulfilled Orao `Randomness` PDA (passed as an account input), verifies it's fulfilled, derives the outcome, and settles â€” all in one tx.\n   120â†’- **Frontend reads** (no tx): Frontend polls the Orao randomness PDA to detect fulfillment and show the result. This is a free read, not a transaction. Frontend maintains a **claimable games list** per user so players can claim or cancel.\n   121â†’- **Failure/timeout**:\n   122â†’  - If Orao has not fulfilled by `resolve_deadline`, any signer can trigger timeout refund (FR-5 invariants).\n   123â†’  - Claim with unfulfilled randomness is rejected.\n   124â†’\n   125â†’**Why not callback**: The 3-tx model (create â†’ join+request â†’ claim+read) is simpler. VRF latency (~1-2s) is absorbed while the frontend detects fulfillment. No callback infrastructure, no extra instruction, no cranker.\n   126â†’\n   127â†’**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   128â†’- [ ] Orao selection is documented in `docs/DECISIONS.md`\n   129â†’- [ ] Shared helper module exists for Orao integration (`vrf_orao.rs`) â€” request helper, read helper, fulfillment check\n   130â†’- [ ] VRF request is embedded in a game instruction (e.g., `join_match`), not a separate instruction\n   131â†’- [ ] `claim_payout` reads Orao randomness account at claim time, derives outcome, and settles\n   132â†’- [ ] Claim emits Anchor event with randomness bytes + derived outcome (audit trail persists in tx logs after match PDA closed)\n   133â†’- [ ] Claim with unfulfilled Orao randomness is rejected with clear error\n   134â†’- [ ] Outcome derivation from VRF is deterministic and uses only on-chain/public inputs\n   135â†’- [ ] Timeout path remains permissionless when VRF is not fulfilled (refund, not stuck funds)\n   136â†’- [ ] `mock-vrf` feature flag: in test builds, skip Orao CPI on request and allow test authority to write mock randomness for claim\n   137â†’- [ ] Reference implementation: Coinflip (001) as first consumer\n   138â†’- [ ] Drop all MagicBlock VRF references from codebase and docs\n   139â†’\n   140â†’### FR-5: On-Chain Lifecycle State Machine\n   141â†’\n   142â†’Every round in every game follows the same phase progression with hard invariants. Not every game uses every phase â€” VRF-only games skip RESOLVING (result is read at claim time).\n   143â†’\n   144â†’```\n   145â†’WAITING -> ACTIVE -> LOCKED -> RESOLVING -> SETTLED\n   146â†’                         \\                \\-> REFUNDED (on timeout or cancel)\n   147â†’                          \\-> SETTLED (VRF games: claim reads result at claim time, skips RESOLVING)\n   148â†’```\n   149â†’\n   150â†’**Phase usage by game type:**\n   151â†’- **VRF-only games** (coinflip, Lord of RNGs, slots): WAITING â†’ LOCKED â†’ SETTLED/REFUNDED. VRF requested at lock, result read at claim. No RESOLVING needed.\n   152â†’- **Commit-reveal games** (crash, chart the course, game of trades): WAITING â†’ ACTIVE â†’ LOCKED â†’ RESOLVING â†’ SETTLED/REFUNDED. Server submits reveal during RESOLVING.\n   153â†’- **Mixed VRF + commit-reveal** (tug of earn): Uses RESOLVING for server reveal phase.\n   154â†’\n   155â†’**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   156â†’- [ ] `RoundPhase` enum: `Waiting`, `Active`, `Locked`, `Resolving`, `Settled`, `Refunded`\n   157â†’- [ ] `transition(current, target) -> Result<()>` validates allowed transitions, rejects invalid ones (including LOCKEDâ†’SETTLED for VRF games)\n   158â†’- [ ] **Timeout invariant**: Every round entering `Locked` or `Resolving` gets a `resolve_deadline` timestamp. After expiry, anyone can trigger refund â€” BUT only if the resolution source (VRF or commit-reveal) has NOT been fulfilled. If VRF is fulfilled, claim must be used instead of timeout_cancel.\n   159â†’- [ ] **Pause invariant**: Global pause (platform-level) and per-game pause (game config). Paused games reject new rounds but existing rounds can still settle or refund.\n   160â†’- [ ] **Refund invariant**: Any round that doesn't reach `Settled` before its deadline AND whose resolution source is not fulfilled is refundable. No player funds get stuck. Refund is not available if a valid result exists (prevents racing claim vs refund).\n   161â†’- [ ] Phase transitions emit Anchor events for frontend consumption\n   162â†’- [ ] Timestamp tracking: `created_at`, `locked_at`, `resolve_deadline`, `settled_at` fields\n   163â†’\n   164â†’### FR-6: Platform CPI Helpers\n   165â†’\n   166â†’Reusable CPI calls from game programs to the platform program for updating player profiles after settlement.\n   167â†’\n   168â†’**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   169â†’- [ ] `update_player_profile(program, profile_pda, game, wins, wager, won)` CPIs into platform program\n   170â†’- [ ] CPI is conditional â€” skipped if player profile PDA does not exist (no hard failure)\n   171â†’- [ ] Both players' profiles updated on settlement (winner and loser stats)\n   172â†’- [ ] CPI helper is generic enough for all game types (accepts game discriminator)\n   173â†’\n   174â†’---\n   175â†’\n   176â†’## Success Criteria\n   177â†’\n   178â†’- Any new game program can import `solana/shared/` and get lifecycle, escrow, fees, timeout, pause, and CPI for free\n   179â†’- Compile-time enforcement: a game that skips fee calculation or lifecycle validation won't compile\n   180â†’- Commit-reveal module passes unit tests with known hash pairs\n   181â†’- Orao 3-tx flow works: join requests VRF, claim reads randomness + settles, timeout refunds if unfulfilled\n   182â†’- No game program contains duplicated fee math, lifecycle logic, or escrow handling\n   183â†’\n   184â†’---\n   185â†’\n   186â†’## Dependencies\n   187â†’\n   188â†’- Existing `solana/shared/` crate (fees, tiers, constants â€” already implemented)\n   189â†’- Platform program (`solana/programs/platform/`) for CPI target\n   190â†’- VRF provider SDK (Orao)\n   191â†’\n   192â†’## Assumptions\n   193â†’\n   194â†’- Program-per-game architecture (not monolith, not shared on-chain kernel)\n   195â†’- Consistency via compile-time shared crate, not CPI at runtime\n   196â†’- V1 hardcoded fees (no on-chain admin configurability)\n   197â†’- Two fairness approaches cover all 8 games: VRF (randomness) + Commit-Reveal (server verification)\n   198â†’- Pyth oracle is a data source, not a fairness mechanism (read directly by contracts)\n   199â†’- No fallback VRF provider for V1; if Orao callback fails or stalls, rounds resolve through timeout refund path\n   200â†’\n   201â†’---\n   202â†’\n   203â†’## Validation Plan\n   204â†’\n   205â†’| # | Acceptance Criterion | Validation Method | Evidence Required |\n   206â†’|---|---------------------|-------------------|-------------------|\n   207â†’| 1 | Escrow deposit/payout/refund works | bankrun tests with SOL transfers | Test output showing balance changes |\n   208â†’| 2 | Commit-reveal verifies correctly | Unit tests with known SHA256 pairs | Test output with pass/fail cases |\n   209â†’| 3 | Fee math is correct | Unit tests: 300 bps, rounding, edge cases | Test output showing fee calculations |\n   210â†’| 4 | Lifecycle rejects invalid transitions | Unit tests for all phase pairs | Test output showing accepted/rejected transitions |\n   211â†’| 5 | Timeout refund is permissionless | bankrun test: any signer can trigger after deadline | Test output showing refund by third party |\n   212â†’| 6 | Pause blocks new rounds | bankrun test: paused game rejects create_round | Test output showing rejection |\n   213â†’| 7 | Orao request + read-at-claim works | bankrun test (mock-vrf): join requests VRF, claim reads + settles. Plus timeout path. | Test output showing 3-tx flow + audit event emitted |\n   214â†’| 8 | CPI updates player profile | bankrun test: settlement updates both profiles | Test output showing profile changes |\n   215â†’\n   216â†’---\n   217â†’\n   218â†’## Completion Signal\n   219â†’\n   220â†’### Implementation Checklist\n   221â†’\n   222â†’**Phase A: Shared Crate Pure Modules** (no program changes, `cargo test -p rng-shared` validates)\n   223â†’\n   224â†’- [x] [on-chain] Create `solana/shared/src/lifecycle.rs` â€” `RoundPhase` enum (`Waiting`, `Active`, `Locked`, `Resolving`, `Settled`, `Refunded`) as `#[derive(AnchorSerialize, AnchorDeserialize, Clone, Copy, PartialEq, Eq)]`. Add `transition(current: RoundPhase, target: RoundPhase) -> Result<()>` that validates allowed transitions (WAITINGâ†’ACTIVE, WAITINGâ†’LOCKED, ACTIVEâ†’LOCKED, LOCKEDâ†’RESOLVING, RESOLVINGâ†’SETTLED, RESOLVINGâ†’REFUNDED, WAITINGâ†’REFUNDED, ACTIVEâ†’REFUNDED, LOCKEDâ†’REFUNDED) and rejects all others. Add `RoundTimestamps` struct with `created_at: i64`, `locked_at: Option<i64>`, `resolve_deadline: Option<i64>`, `settled_at: Option<i64>`. Re-export from `lib.rs`. Unit tests: all valid transitions pass, all invalid transitions fail, enum serialization round-trips. Verify: `cargo test -p rng-shared`. (done: iteration 1)\n   225â†’\n   226â†’- [x] [on-chain] Create `solana/shared/src/timeout.rs` â€” `is_expired(resolve_deadline: i64, now: i64) -> bool` returns true when `now >= resolve_deadline`. `enforce_not_expired(resolve_deadline: i64, now: i64) -> Result<()>` returns error if expired. `DEFAULT_RESOLVE_TIMEOUT_SECONDS: i64 = 120`. Error type: `TimeoutError::ResolveDeadlineExceeded`. Unit tests: boundary conditions (exactly at deadline, 1 second before, 1 second after). Keep existing `LOCK_TIMEOUT_SECONDS` in `constants.rs` for backwards compat during migration. Re-export from `lib.rs`. Verify: `cargo test -p rng-shared`. (done: iteration 2)\n   227â†’\n   228â†’- [x] [on-chain] Create `solana/shared/src/commit_reveal.rs` â€” `store_commitment(commitment: &mut [u8; 32], hash: [u8; 32])` writes hash to the provided storage. `verify_reveal(commitment: &[u8; 32], server_seed: &[u8]) -> Result<()>` computes `solana_program::hash::hashv(&[server_seed])` and compares with commitment; returns `CommitRevealError::CommitmentMismatch` on failure. Error type: `#[error_code] CommitRevealError { CommitmentMismatch }`. Unit tests: known SHA256 pair passes, tampered seed fails, empty seed fails. Re-export from `lib.rs`. Verify: `cargo test -p rng-shared`. (done: iteration 3)\n   229â†’\n   230â†’- [x] [on-chain] Update `solana/shared/src/fees.rs` â€” Add `calculate_net_payout(pool: u64) -> (u64, u64)` returning `(fee, net_payout)` where `net_payout = pool - fee`. Add `MAX_FEE_BPS: u16 = 1000` compile-time safety cap. Add `#[cfg(test)]` test for `calculate_net_payout` (e.g., pool=1_000_000 â†’ fee=30_000, net=970_000). Keep all existing functions and tests passing unchanged. Re-export new items from `lib.rs`. Verify: `cargo test -p rng-shared`. (done: iteration 4)\n   231â†’\n   232â†’- [x] [on-chain] Create `solana/shared/src/pause.rs` â€” `check_not_paused(global_paused: bool, game_paused: bool) -> Result<()>` returns `PauseError::PlatformPaused` or `PauseError::GamePaused`. Error type: `#[error_code] PauseError { PlatformPaused, GamePaused }`. This is a pure validation helper â€” games pass their config flags in. Unit tests: both flags false â†’ Ok, global true â†’ PlatformPaused, game true â†’ GamePaused, both true â†’ PlatformPaused (global takes precedence). Re-export from `lib.rs`. Verify: `cargo test -p rng-shared`. (done: iteration 5)\n   233â†’\n   234â†’- [ ] [on-chain] Create `solana/shared/src/escrow.rs` â€” Helper functions for raw lamport transfers: `transfer_lamports_from_pda(pda: &AccountInfo, recipient: &AccountInfo, amount: u64) -> Result<()>` using `try_borrow_mut_lamports` pattern (extracted from coinflip's claim_payout.rs). `transfer_lamports_to_pda(from: &AccountInfo, pda: &AccountInfo, amount: u64, system_program: &AccountInfo) -> Result<()>` using `system_program::transfer` CPI. Error types: `EscrowError::InsufficientEscrowBalance`. Unit tests may be limited (lamport transfers need runtime); add doc-tests with usage examples. Re-export from `lib.rs`. Verify: `anchor build` succeeds (tests that need runtime context deferred to bankrun in Phase C).\n   235â†’\n   236â†’- [ ] [on-chain] Create `solana/shared/src/cpi.rs` â€” Extract platform CPI helper from coinflip's `claim_payout.rs`. Function signature: `update_player_profile_cpi(platform_program: &AccountInfo, profile: &AccountInfo, authority: &AccountInfo, signer_seeds: &[&[u8]], total_games_delta: u64, wins_delta: u64, total_wagered_delta: u64, total_won_delta: u64) -> Result<()>`. Guard: if `profile.data_is_empty()`, skip silently (return Ok). Uses `platform::cpi::update_player_profile` with CpiContext. Re-export from `lib.rs`. Verify: `anchor build` succeeds.\n   237â†’\n   238â†’**Phase B: Orao VRF Integration**\n   239â†’\n   240â†’- [ ] [on-chain] Add `orao-solana-vrf` dependency to `solana/Cargo.toml` workspace deps (with `cpi` feature). Create `solana/shared/src/vrf_orao.rs` with: `VrfAuditFields` struct (`vrf_request_key: Pubkey`, `vrf_requested_at: i64`). Helper `request_orao_randomness(orao_program, network_state, treasury, random, payer, system_program, seed: [u8; 32]) -> Result<()>` that CPIs into Orao's request instruction. Helper `read_orao_randomness(randomness_account: &AccountInfo) -> Result<[u8; 32]>` that reads fulfilled randomness from Orao's `RandomnessAccountData`. `is_fulfilled(randomness: &[u8; 32]) -> bool` checks if randomness is non-zero (all-zeros = unfulfilled). Add `mock-vrf` feature flag to shared crate: under `mock-vrf`, `request_orao_randomness` is a no-op and `read_orao_randomness` reads from a simple test account instead of Orao's type. Re-export from `lib.rs`. Verify: `anchor build` succeeds.\n   241â†’\n   242â†’**Phase C: Coinflip Rewrite** (validates all shared modules end-to-end via the 3-tx flow: create â†’ join+request â†’ claim+read)\n   243â†’\n   244â†’- [ ] [on-chain] Rewrite `solana/programs/coinflip/src/state.rs` â€” Replace `phase: u8` with `phase: RoundPhase` from shared crate. Add fields: `resolve_deadline: i64`, `vrf_request_key: Pubkey` (Orao randomness PDA address, used to look up result at claim time). Add `paused: bool` to `CoinflipConfig`. Remove `oracle_authority` from config (Orao uses account constraints, not signer trust). Remove `ephemeral-vrf-sdk` from `Cargo.toml`, add `orao-solana-vrf` workspace dep. Update `CoinflipMatch` seeds and space calculation. Add `MatchSettled` Anchor event struct: `creator`, `opponent`, `winner`, `randomness: [u8; 32]`, `payout_amount`, `fee_amount`. Verify: `anchor build` succeeds (tests will fail â€” expected, fixed in later iterations).\n   245â†’\n   246â†’- [ ] [on-chain] Rewrite `create_match.rs` + `cancel_match.rs` â€” `create_match`: use `shared::lifecycle::transition` for initial phase (Waiting), use `shared::pause::check_not_paused(config.paused, false)`, use `shared::escrow::transfer_lamports_to_pda` for deposit, set `created_at` timestamp. `cancel_match`: use `shared::lifecycle::transition(current, Refunded)`, use `shared::escrow::transfer_lamports_from_pda` for refund, close match PDA. Both instructions use shared `RoundPhase` enum instead of raw u8 phase constants. Verify: `anchor build` succeeds.\n   247â†’\n   248â†’- [ ] [on-chain] Rewrite `join_match.rs` â€” Remove all `ephemeral_vrf_sdk` imports and `#[vrf]` macro. Use `shared::escrow::transfer_lamports_to_pda` for opponent deposit. Transition phase `Waiting â†’ Locked` via `shared::lifecycle::transition`. In the same instruction, call `shared::vrf_orao::request_orao_randomness` to CPI into Orao (pass Orao program + accounts). Store `vrf_request_key` (Orao randomness PDA address) on match. Set `resolve_deadline = now + DEFAULT_RESOLVE_TIMEOUT_SECONDS`. Under `mock-vrf` feature: skip Orao CPI (request is no-op). Verify: `anchor build` succeeds.\n   249â†’\n   250â†’- [ ] [on-chain] Rewrite `claim_payout.rs` â€” This replaces both old `resolve_match` and `claim_payout`. Single instruction does: (1) check `phase == Locked` and `!claimed`, (2) read Orao randomness account via `shared::vrf_orao::read_orao_randomness` â€” reject if not fulfilled, (3) derive winner via `shared::constants::from_randomness(randomness[0])`, (4) compute fee/payout via `shared::fees::calculate_net_payout`, (5) transfer payout to winner + fee to treasury via `shared::escrow::transfer_lamports_from_pda`, (6) CPI update both player profiles via `shared::cpi::update_player_profile_cpi`, (7) emit `MatchSettled` event with randomness + winner + amounts, (8) set `phase = Settled`, `claimed = true`, close match PDA. Either player can call â€” payout goes to derived winner regardless. Under `mock-vrf`: read mock randomness account instead of Orao. Delete old `resolve_match.rs`. Verify: `anchor build` succeeds.\n   251â†’\n   252â†’- [ ] [on-chain] Rewrite `timeout_cancel.rs` â€” Check `phase == Locked`, check `shared::timeout::is_expired(resolve_deadline, now)`, check that Orao randomness is NOT fulfilled via `shared::vrf_orao::is_fulfilled` (reject if VRF resolved â€” must use claim instead), use `shared::escrow::transfer_lamports_from_pda` for refunds to both players, transition to `Refunded` via `shared::lifecycle::transition`, close match PDA. Permissionless â€” any signer can trigger after deadline, but only when result is genuinely unavailable. Verify: `anchor build` succeeds.\n   253â†’\n   254â†’- [ ] [test] Rewrite `solana/tests/coinflip.ts` bankrun tests for new 3-tx program â€” Setup: deploy coinflip + platform programs with `mock-vrf` feature, initialize configs. Tests: create_match (phase=Waiting, escrow correct, pause check), join_match (phase=Locked, escrow doubled, vrf_request_key set, resolve_deadline set), claim_payout with mock randomness (reads mock account, derives winner HEADS/TAILS, fee math correct, treasury transfer, profile CPI for both players, MatchSettled event emitted, match PDA closed), cancel_match (Waiting-only, full refund), timeout_cancel (after resolve_deadline expired AND VRF unfulfilled, permissionless, both players refunded), error cases (invalid phase transitions, double-claim, unauthorized, self-join, claim with unfulfilled randomness rejected, timeout_cancel rejected when VRF IS fulfilled â€” must claim instead). Target: all tests green. Verify: `anchor test --skip-local-validator`.\n   255â†’\n   256â†’- [ ] [engine] Re-run `scripts/sync-idl` to update `packages/anchor-client/` with new coinflip IDL (new CoinflipMatch shape with RoundPhase + vrf_request_key, removed resolve_match instruction, updated claim_payout accounts to include Orao randomness). Verify: `anchor build && pnpm lint` in anchor-client package.\n   257â†’\n   258â†’- [ ] [docs] Drop all MagicBlock VRF references from codebase: update `sources/rng-utopia/CLAUDE.md` locked decisions table (MagicBlock â†’ Orao), remove MagicBlock comments from coinflip source files, clean up any remaining `ephemeral-vrf-sdk` references. Verify: `grep -r \"MagicBlock\\|ephemeral.vrf\" sources/rng-utopia/solana/ sources/rng-utopia/CLAUDE.md` returns zero matches.\n   259â†’\n   260â†’### Testing Requirements\n   261â†’\n   262â†’The agent MUST complete ALL before outputting the completion signal:\n   263â†’\n   264â†’#### Code Quality\n   265â†’- [ ] All existing tests pass\n   266â†’- [ ] New tests added for each shared module\n   267â†’- [ ] No lint errors\n   268â†’\n   269â†’#### Functional Verification\n   270â†’- [ ] All acceptance criteria verified\n   271â†’- [ ] Edge cases handled (zero amounts, expired deadlines, double-settle, paused state)\n   272â†’- [ ] Error states handled (invalid transitions, commitment mismatch, insufficient funds)\n   273â†’\n   274â†’#### Console/Network Check\n   275â†’- [ ] `anchor build` succeeds\n   276â†’- [ ] `anchor test` passes all program tests\n   277â†’\n   278â†’### Iteration Instructions\n   279â†’\n   280â†’If ANY check fails:\n   281â†’1. Identify the specific issue\n   282â†’2. Fix the code\n   283â†’3. Re-run tests\n   284â†’4. Re-verify all criteria\n   285â†’5. Check again\n   286â†’\n   287â†’**Only when ALL checks pass, output:** `<promise>DONE</promise>`\n   288â†’\n   289â†’### Post-Completion: Gap Analysis\n   290â†’\n   291â†’After the spec loop outputs `<promise>DONE</promise>`, `spec-loop.sh` automatically runs\n   292â†’`/gap-analysis {id} --non-interactive` which:\n   293â†’1. Audits every FR acceptance criterion against the codebase\n   294â†’2. Writes `docs/specs/004-shared-infrastructure/gap-analysis.md` with inventory + audit + recommendations\n   295â†’3. Annotates FR checkboxes with HTML comment evidence (`<!-- satisfied: ... -->`)\n   296â†’4. Commits everything together with the completion commit\n   297â†’"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"3ef31b5a-f057-490b-97be-2b7d8a2c562f","uuid":"05fb4094-d478-429e-87fc-9efc9c300046","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspaces/rng-utopia/docs/specs/004-shared-infrastructure/spec.md","content":"# Specification: 004 Shared Infrastructure\n\n## Meta\n\n| Field | Value |\n|-------|-------|\n| Status | Ready |\n| Priority | P0 |\n| Phase | 1 |\n| NR_OF_TRIES | 5 |\n\n---\n\n## Overview\n\nShared Infrastructure defines the common Rust crate (`solana/shared/`) that all game programs depend on. It provides escrow helpers, a standardized lifecycle state machine, timeout/refund logic, pause controls, a commit-reveal verifier, fee distribution, and platform CPI helpers. Every game compiles against this crate â€” consistency is enforced at compile time, not via CPI at runtime.\n\nThis spec formalizes the architecture approved in the pivot doc (`docs/pivot-doc.md`) and blocks all game implementations.\n\n## User Stories\n\n- As a game developer, I want a shared lifecycle state machine so that every game follows the same round phases and invariants without reimplementation.\n- As a player, I want timeout refunds to be permissionless so that my funds are never stuck in an unresolved round.\n- As an auditor, I want fee math in a single crate so that I audit money-handling once and trust it everywhere.\n- As an operator, I want global and per-game pause controls so that I can halt new rounds without blocking in-progress settlements.\n\n---\n\n## Scope Alignment\n\n- **`docs/SCOPE.md` references**: Section 3 (Architecture Direction), Section 4 (Source of Truth), Section 6 (Functional Requirements - on-chain settlement)\n- **Scope status**: V1 In Scope\n- **Phase boundary**: Phase 1 (blocks Coinflip rewrite and all subsequent games)\n\n## Required Context Files\n\n- `docs/pivot-doc.md` (Architecture Decision â€” canonical source for this spec)\n- `docs/FOUNDATIONS.md` Â§2 (On-Chain Dev Loop), Â§5 (Randomness Strategy), Â§8 (Fee Math)\n- `docs/SCOPE.md` (scope boundary)\n- `solana/shared/` (existing crate â€” partial implementation)\n\n## Contract Files\n\n- `solana/shared/src/lib.rs` â€” crate root (existing)\n- `solana/shared/src/fees.rs` â€” fee calculation (existing, to be formalized)\n- `solana/shared/src/tiers.rs` â€” tier definitions (existing)\n- `solana/shared/src/constants.rs` â€” constants (existing)\n- `solana/shared/src/lifecycle.rs` â€” lifecycle state machine (to be created)\n- `solana/shared/src/escrow.rs` â€” escrow helpers (to be created)\n- `solana/shared/src/timeout.rs` â€” timeout logic (to be created)\n- `solana/shared/src/pause.rs` â€” pause controls (to be created)\n- `solana/shared/src/commit_reveal.rs` â€” commit-reveal verifier (to be created)\n- `solana/shared/src/cpi.rs` â€” platform CPI helpers (to be created)\n- `solana/shared/src/vrf_orao.rs` â€” Orao request/callback helpers (to be created)\n\n---\n\n## Functional Requirements\n\n### FR-1: Shared Crate â€” Escrow Helpers (Claim-Based Payout)\n\nReusable functions for depositing SOL to a round PDA and letting participants claim their funds. Uses a **claim-based payout pattern**: for VRF games, the `claim_payout` instruction reads the VRF result at claim time (no separate settle tx), derives the winner, and transfers funds â€” all in one tx. For commit-reveal games, the server's reveal instruction writes the outcome, then players claim. Either way, the claim instruction is what moves funds.\n\n**Three-transaction flow for VRF games (e.g., coinflip):**\n1. `create_match` â€” creator deposits SOL, phase = WAITING\n2. `join_match` â€” opponent deposits SOL, requests Orao VRF, phase = LOCKED, `resolve_deadline` set\n3. `claim_payout` â€” either player calls. Reads fulfilled Orao randomness account, derives winner, transfers payout + fee, emits audit event, closes match.\n\nFrontend reads the Orao randomness PDA (free, no tx) to show the result. The claim tx is what settles on-chain.\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- [ ] `deposit_to_escrow(from, round_pda, amount)` transfers SOL from player to round PDA via system program CPI\n- [ ] `claim_payout` reads VRF result at claim time (for VRF games) or reads stored outcome (for commit-reveal games), derives winner, transfers payout\n- [ ] Either participant can trigger claim â€” payout always goes to the derived winner regardless of caller\n- [ ] Claim is idempotent â€” double-claim returns error, does not double-pay\n- [ ] Claim emits an Anchor event with VRF randomness bytes, derived winner, and payout amounts (audit trail â€” match PDA is closed after claim)\n- [ ] `refund(round_pda, caller)` â€” each depositor calls individually to pull their refund after timeout\n- [ ] `close_round(round_pda, rent_recipient)` closes the PDA and returns rent\n- [ ] No escrow function touches fee math (fees handled separately in FR-3)\n- [ ] **Claimable games query**: match PDAs in LOCKED phase (VRF fulfilled) or SETTLED phase (commit-reveal settled) with `claimed == false` are discoverable via `getProgramAccounts` filter by player pubkey + phase. Frontend must maintain a \"claimable / unresolved games\" list per user.\n\n### FR-2: Commit-Reveal Verifier\n\nSelf-built module (~50 lines Rust) for server result verification. The server commits a hash before/at round start, then reveals the seed at settlement. The contract verifies the commitment.\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- [ ] `store_commitment(round_pda, hash)` stores `SHA256(server_seed)` in the round PDA\n- [ ] `verify_reveal(round_pda, server_seed)` checks `SHA256(server_seed) == stored_hash`\n- [ ] Verification failure returns a typed error (commitment mismatch)\n- [ ] On verification failure, round transitions to REFUNDED (not SETTLED)\n- [ ] No third-party dependency â€” uses `solana_program::hash::hashv` or equivalent\n- [ ] Module is independently testable (unit tests with known hash pairs)\n\n### FR-3: Fee Distribution\n\nFormalize existing fee math as the single path for all fee calculations. No game ever implements its own fee logic.\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- [ ] `calculate_fee(pool_lamports) -> (fee, net_payout)` returns fee and payout amounts\n- [ ] Fee = 300 bps (3%) of pool, hardcoded constant\n- [ ] `transfer_fee(round_pda, treasury_pda, fee_amount)` sends fee to treasury\n- [ ] Integer math only (basis points, lamports) â€” no floats\n- [ ] Rounding favors the player (fee rounds down)\n- [ ] `MAX_FEE_BPS = 1000` compile-time safety cap preserved\n- [ ] Fee split (200 bps revenue, 70 bps rakeback, 30 bps chest) tracked but single treasury transfer for V1\n\n### FR-4: VRF Provider Integration (Orao)\n\nIntegrate **Orao** as the single VRF provider for all games requiring randomness. Uses `orao-solana-vrf` (standard crate, not callback variant). No separate consume/resolve instruction â€” VRF result is read at claim time.\n\n**Integration Contract (Authoritative Shape):**\n\n- **Request path**: VRF is requested as part of an existing game instruction (e.g., `join_match` for coinflip). No separate `request_vrf` instruction.\n- **Request side effects**:\n  - CPIs into Orao to request randomness with a unique seed (derived from match PDA or round ID).\n  - Stores `vrf_request_key` on the round account for later lookup.\n  - Sets `resolve_deadline` for timeout safety.\n  - Moves phase to `Locked`.\n- **Read-at-claim path**: No separate consume/callback instruction. The `claim_payout` instruction reads the fulfilled Orao `Randomness` PDA (passed as an account input), verifies it's fulfilled, derives the outcome, and settles â€” all in one tx.\n- **Frontend reads** (no tx): Frontend polls the Orao randomness PDA to detect fulfillment and show the result. This is a free read, not a transaction. Frontend maintains a **claimable games list** per user so players can claim or cancel.\n- **Failure/timeout**:\n  - If Orao has not fulfilled by `resolve_deadline`, any signer can trigger timeout refund (FR-5 invariants).\n  - Claim with unfulfilled randomness is rejected.\n\n**Why not callback**: The 3-tx model (create â†’ join+request â†’ claim+read) is simpler. VRF latency (~1-2s) is absorbed while the frontend detects fulfillment. No callback infrastructure, no extra instruction, no cranker.\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- [ ] Orao selection is documented in `docs/DECISIONS.md`\n- [ ] Shared helper module exists for Orao integration (`vrf_orao.rs`) â€” request helper, read helper, fulfillment check\n- [ ] VRF request is embedded in a game instruction (e.g., `join_match`), not a separate instruction\n- [ ] `claim_payout` reads Orao randomness account at claim time, derives outcome, and settles\n- [ ] Claim emits Anchor event with randomness bytes + derived outcome (audit trail persists in tx logs after match PDA closed)\n- [ ] Claim with unfulfilled Orao randomness is rejected with clear error\n- [ ] Outcome derivation from VRF is deterministic and uses only on-chain/public inputs\n- [ ] Timeout path remains permissionless when VRF is not fulfilled (refund, not stuck funds)\n- [ ] `mock-vrf` feature flag: in test builds, skip Orao CPI on request and allow test authority to write mock randomness for claim\n- [ ] Reference implementation: Coinflip (001) as first consumer\n- [ ] Drop all MagicBlock VRF references from codebase and docs\n\n### FR-5: On-Chain Lifecycle State Machine\n\nEvery round in every game follows the same phase progression with hard invariants. Not every game uses every phase â€” VRF-only games skip RESOLVING (result is read at claim time).\n\n```\nWAITING -> ACTIVE -> LOCKED -> RESOLVING -> SETTLED\n                         \\                \\-> REFUNDED (on timeout or cancel)\n                          \\-> SETTLED (VRF games: claim reads result at claim time, skips RESOLVING)\n```\n\n**Phase usage by game type:**\n- **VRF-only games** (coinflip, Lord of RNGs, slots): WAITING â†’ LOCKED â†’ SETTLED/REFUNDED. VRF requested at lock, result read at claim. No RESOLVING needed.\n- **Commit-reveal games** (crash, chart the course, game of trades): WAITING â†’ ACTIVE â†’ LOCKED â†’ RESOLVING â†’ SETTLED/REFUNDED. Server submits reveal during RESOLVING.\n- **Mixed VRF + commit-reveal** (tug of earn): Uses RESOLVING for server reveal phase.\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- [ ] `RoundPhase` enum: `Waiting`, `Active`, `Locked`, `Resolving`, `Settled`, `Refunded`\n- [ ] `transition(current, target) -> Result<()>` validates allowed transitions, rejects invalid ones (including LOCKEDâ†’SETTLED for VRF games)\n- [ ] **Timeout invariant**: Every round entering `Locked` or `Resolving` gets a `resolve_deadline` timestamp. After expiry, anyone can trigger refund â€” BUT only if the resolution source (VRF or commit-reveal) has NOT been fulfilled. If VRF is fulfilled, claim must be used instead of timeout_cancel.\n- [ ] **Pause invariant**: Global pause (platform-level) and per-game pause (game config). Paused games reject new rounds but existing rounds can still settle or refund.\n- [ ] **Refund invariant**: Any round that doesn't reach `Settled` before its deadline AND whose resolution source is not fulfilled is refundable. No player funds get stuck. Refund is not available if a valid result exists (prevents racing claim vs refund).\n- [ ] Phase transitions emit Anchor events for frontend consumption\n- [ ] Timestamp tracking: `created_at`, `locked_at`, `resolve_deadline`, `settled_at` fields\n\n### FR-6: Platform CPI Helpers\n\nReusable CPI calls from game programs to the platform program for updating player profiles after settlement.\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- [ ] `update_player_profile(program, profile_pda, game, wins, wager, won)` CPIs into platform program\n- [ ] CPI is conditional â€” skipped if player profile PDA does not exist (no hard failure)\n- [ ] Both players' profiles updated on settlement (winner and loser stats)\n- [ ] CPI helper is generic enough for all game types (accepts game discriminator)\n\n---\n\n## Success Criteria\n\n- Any new game program can import `solana/shared/` and get lifecycle, escrow, fees, timeout, pause, and CPI for free\n- Compile-time enforcement: a game that skips fee calculation or lifecycle validation won't compile\n- Commit-reveal module passes unit tests with known hash pairs\n- Orao 3-tx flow works: join requests VRF, claim reads randomness + settles, timeout refunds if unfulfilled\n- No game program contains duplicated fee math, lifecycle logic, or escrow handling\n\n---\n\n## Dependencies\n\n- Existing `solana/shared/` crate (fees, tiers, constants â€” already implemented)\n- Platform program (`solana/programs/platform/`) for CPI target\n- VRF provider SDK (Orao)\n\n## Assumptions\n\n- Program-per-game architecture (not monolith, not shared on-chain kernel)\n- Consistency via compile-time shared crate, not CPI at runtime\n- V1 hardcoded fees (no on-chain admin configurability)\n- Two fairness approaches cover all 8 games: VRF (randomness) + Commit-Reveal (server verification)\n- Pyth oracle is a data source, not a fairness mechanism (read directly by contracts)\n- No fallback VRF provider for V1; if Orao callback fails or stalls, rounds resolve through timeout refund path\n\n---\n\n## Validation Plan\n\n| # | Acceptance Criterion | Validation Method | Evidence Required |\n|---|---------------------|-------------------|-------------------|\n| 1 | Escrow deposit/payout/refund works | bankrun tests with SOL transfers | Test output showing balance changes |\n| 2 | Commit-reveal verifies correctly | Unit tests with known SHA256 pairs | Test output with pass/fail cases |\n| 3 | Fee math is correct | Unit tests: 300 bps, rounding, edge cases | Test output showing fee calculations |\n| 4 | Lifecycle rejects invalid transitions | Unit tests for all phase pairs | Test output showing accepted/rejected transitions |\n| 5 | Timeout refund is permissionless | bankrun test: any signer can trigger after deadline | Test output showing refund by third party |\n| 6 | Pause blocks new rounds | bankrun test: paused game rejects create_round | Test output showing rejection |\n| 7 | Orao request + read-at-claim works | bankrun test (mock-vrf): join requests VRF, claim reads + settles. Plus timeout path. | Test output showing 3-tx flow + audit event emitted |\n| 8 | CPI updates player profile | bankrun test: settlement updates both profiles | Test output showing profile changes |\n\n---\n\n## Completion Signal\n\n### Implementation Checklist\n\n**Phase A: Shared Crate Pure Modules** (no program changes, `cargo test -p rng-shared` validates)\n\n- [x] [on-chain] Create `solana/shared/src/lifecycle.rs` â€” `RoundPhase` enum (`Waiting`, `Active`, `Locked`, `Resolving`, `Settled`, `Refunded`) as `#[derive(AnchorSerialize, AnchorDeserialize, Clone, Copy, PartialEq, Eq)]`. Add `transition(current: RoundPhase, target: RoundPhase) -> Result<()>` that validates allowed transitions (WAITINGâ†’ACTIVE, WAITINGâ†’LOCKED, ACTIVEâ†’LOCKED, LOCKEDâ†’RESOLVING, RESOLVINGâ†’SETTLED, RESOLVINGâ†’REFUNDED, WAITINGâ†’REFUNDED, ACTIVEâ†’REFUNDED, LOCKEDâ†’REFUNDED) and rejects all others. Add `RoundTimestamps` struct with `created_at: i64`, `locked_at: Option<i64>`, `resolve_deadline: Option<i64>`, `settled_at: Option<i64>`. Re-export from `lib.rs`. Unit tests: all valid transitions pass, all invalid transitions fail, enum serialization round-trips. Verify: `cargo test -p rng-shared`. (done: iteration 1)\n\n- [x] [on-chain] Create `solana/shared/src/timeout.rs` â€” `is_expired(resolve_deadline: i64, now: i64) -> bool` returns true when `now >= resolve_deadline`. `enforce_not_expired(resolve_deadline: i64, now: i64) -> Result<()>` returns error if expired. `DEFAULT_RESOLVE_TIMEOUT_SECONDS: i64 = 120`. Error type: `TimeoutError::ResolveDeadlineExceeded`. Unit tests: boundary conditions (exactly at deadline, 1 second before, 1 second after). Keep existing `LOCK_TIMEOUT_SECONDS` in `constants.rs` for backwards compat during migration. Re-export from `lib.rs`. Verify: `cargo test -p rng-shared`. (done: iteration 2)\n\n- [x] [on-chain] Create `solana/shared/src/commit_reveal.rs` â€” `store_commitment(commitment: &mut [u8; 32], hash: [u8; 32])` writes hash to the provided storage. `verify_reveal(commitment: &[u8; 32], server_seed: &[u8]) -> Result<()>` computes `solana_program::hash::hashv(&[server_seed])` and compares with commitment; returns `CommitRevealError::CommitmentMismatch` on failure. Error type: `#[error_code] CommitRevealError { CommitmentMismatch }`. Unit tests: known SHA256 pair passes, tampered seed fails, empty seed fails. Re-export from `lib.rs`. Verify: `cargo test -p rng-shared`. (done: iteration 3)\n\n- [x] [on-chain] Update `solana/shared/src/fees.rs` â€” Add `calculate_net_payout(pool: u64) -> (u64, u64)` returning `(fee, net_payout)` where `net_payout = pool - fee`. Add `MAX_FEE_BPS: u16 = 1000` compile-time safety cap. Add `#[cfg(test)]` test for `calculate_net_payout` (e.g., pool=1_000_000 â†’ fee=30_000, net=970_000). Keep all existing functions and tests passing unchanged. Re-export new items from `lib.rs`. Verify: `cargo test -p rng-shared`. (done: iteration 4)\n\n- [x] [on-chain] Create `solana/shared/src/pause.rs` â€” `check_not_paused(global_paused: bool, game_paused: bool) -> Result<()>` returns `PauseError::PlatformPaused` or `PauseError::GamePaused`. Error type: `#[error_code] PauseError { PlatformPaused, GamePaused }`. This is a pure validation helper â€” games pass their config flags in. Unit tests: both flags false â†’ Ok, global true â†’ PlatformPaused, game true â†’ GamePaused, both true â†’ PlatformPaused (global takes precedence). Re-export from `lib.rs`. Verify: `cargo test -p rng-shared`. (done: iteration 5)\n\n- [ ] [on-chain] Create `solana/shared/src/escrow.rs` â€” Helper functions for raw lamport transfers: `transfer_lamports_from_pda(pda: &AccountInfo, recipient: &AccountInfo, amount: u64) -> Result<()>` using `try_borrow_mut_lamports` pattern (extracted from coinflip's claim_payout.rs). `transfer_lamports_to_pda(from: &AccountInfo, pda: &AccountInfo, amount: u64, system_program: &AccountInfo) -> Result<()>` using `system_program::transfer` CPI. Error types: `EscrowError::InsufficientEscrowBalance`. Unit tests may be limited (lamport transfers need runtime); add doc-tests with usage examples. Re-export from `lib.rs`. Verify: `anchor build` succeeds (tests that need runtime context deferred to bankrun in Phase C).\n\n- [ ] [on-chain] Create `solana/shared/src/cpi.rs` â€” Extract platform CPI helper from coinflip's `claim_payout.rs`. Function signature: `update_player_profile_cpi(platform_program: &AccountInfo, profile: &AccountInfo, authority: &AccountInfo, signer_seeds: &[&[u8]], total_games_delta: u64, wins_delta: u64, total_wagered_delta: u64, total_won_delta: u64) -> Result<()>`. Guard: if `profile.data_is_empty()`, skip silently (return Ok). Uses `platform::cpi::update_player_profile` with CpiContext. Re-export from `lib.rs`. Verify: `anchor build` succeeds.\n\n**Phase B: Orao VRF Integration**\n\n- [ ] [on-chain] Add `orao-solana-vrf` dependency to `solana/Cargo.toml` workspace deps (with `cpi` feature). Create `solana/shared/src/vrf_orao.rs` with: `VrfAuditFields` struct (`vrf_request_key: Pubkey`, `vrf_requested_at: i64`). Helper `request_orao_randomness(orao_program, network_state, treasury, random, payer, system_program, seed: [u8; 32]) -> Result<()>` that CPIs into Orao's request instruction. Helper `read_orao_randomness(randomness_account: &AccountInfo) -> Result<[u8; 32]>` that reads fulfilled randomness from Orao's `RandomnessAccountData`. `is_fulfilled(randomness: &[u8; 32]) -> bool` checks if randomness is non-zero (all-zeros = unfulfilled). Add `mock-vrf` feature flag to shared crate: under `mock-vrf`, `request_orao_randomness` is a no-op and `read_orao_randomness` reads from a simple test account instead of Orao's type. Re-export from `lib.rs`. Verify: `anchor build` succeeds.\n\n**Phase C: Coinflip Rewrite** (validates all shared modules end-to-end via the 3-tx flow: create â†’ join+request â†’ claim+read)\n\n- [ ] [on-chain] Rewrite `solana/programs/coinflip/src/state.rs` â€” Replace `phase: u8` with `phase: RoundPhase` from shared crate. Add fields: `resolve_deadline: i64`, `vrf_request_key: Pubkey` (Orao randomness PDA address, used to look up result at claim time). Add `paused: bool` to `CoinflipConfig`. Remove `oracle_authority` from config (Orao uses account constraints, not signer trust). Remove `ephemeral-vrf-sdk` from `Cargo.toml`, add `orao-solana-vrf` workspace dep. Update `CoinflipMatch` seeds and space calculation. Add `MatchSettled` Anchor event struct: `creator`, `opponent`, `winner`, `randomness: [u8; 32]`, `payout_amount`, `fee_amount`. Verify: `anchor build` succeeds (tests will fail â€” expected, fixed in later iterations).\n\n- [ ] [on-chain] Rewrite `create_match.rs` + `cancel_match.rs` â€” `create_match`: use `shared::lifecycle::transition` for initial phase (Waiting), use `shared::pause::check_not_paused(config.paused, false)`, use `shared::escrow::transfer_lamports_to_pda` for deposit, set `created_at` timestamp. `cancel_match`: use `shared::lifecycle::transition(current, Refunded)`, use `shared::escrow::transfer_lamports_from_pda` for refund, close match PDA. Both instructions use shared `RoundPhase` enum instead of raw u8 phase constants. Verify: `anchor build` succeeds.\n\n- [ ] [on-chain] Rewrite `join_match.rs` â€” Remove all `ephemeral_vrf_sdk` imports and `#[vrf]` macro. Use `shared::escrow::transfer_lamports_to_pda` for opponent deposit. Transition phase `Waiting â†’ Locked` via `shared::lifecycle::transition`. In the same instruction, call `shared::vrf_orao::request_orao_randomness` to CPI into Orao (pass Orao program + accounts). Store `vrf_request_key` (Orao randomness PDA address) on match. Set `resolve_deadline = now + DEFAULT_RESOLVE_TIMEOUT_SECONDS`. Under `mock-vrf` feature: skip Orao CPI (request is no-op). Verify: `anchor build` succeeds.\n\n- [ ] [on-chain] Rewrite `claim_payout.rs` â€” This replaces both old `resolve_match` and `claim_payout`. Single instruction does: (1) check `phase == Locked` and `!claimed`, (2) read Orao randomness account via `shared::vrf_orao::read_orao_randomness` â€” reject if not fulfilled, (3) derive winner via `shared::constants::from_randomness(randomness[0])`, (4) compute fee/payout via `shared::fees::calculate_net_payout`, (5) transfer payout to winner + fee to treasury via `shared::escrow::transfer_lamports_from_pda`, (6) CPI update both player profiles via `shared::cpi::update_player_profile_cpi`, (7) emit `MatchSettled` event with randomness + winner + amounts, (8) set `phase = Settled`, `claimed = true`, close match PDA. Either player can call â€” payout goes to derived winner regardless. Under `mock-vrf`: read mock randomness account instead of Orao. Delete old `resolve_match.rs`. Verify: `anchor build` succeeds.\n\n- [ ] [on-chain] Rewrite `timeout_cancel.rs` â€” Check `phase == Locked`, check `shared::timeout::is_expired(resolve_deadline, now)`, check that Orao randomness is NOT fulfilled via `shared::vrf_orao::is_fulfilled` (reject if VRF resolved â€” must use claim instead), use `shared::escrow::transfer_lamports_from_pda` for refunds to both players, transition to `Refunded` via `shared::lifecycle::transition`, close match PDA. Permissionless â€” any signer can trigger after deadline, but only when result is genuinely unavailable. Verify: `anchor build` succeeds.\n\n- [ ] [test] Rewrite `solana/tests/coinflip.ts` bankrun tests for new 3-tx program â€” Setup: deploy coinflip + platform programs with `mock-vrf` feature, initialize configs. Tests: create_match (phase=Waiting, escrow correct, pause check), join_match (phase=Locked, escrow doubled, vrf_request_key set, resolve_deadline set), claim_payout with mock randomness (reads mock account, derives winner HEADS/TAILS, fee math correct, treasury transfer, profile CPI for both players, MatchSettled event emitted, match PDA closed), cancel_match (Waiting-only, full refund), timeout_cancel (after resolve_deadline expired AND VRF unfulfilled, permissionless, both players refunded), error cases (invalid phase transitions, double-claim, unauthorized, self-join, claim with unfulfilled randomness rejected, timeout_cancel rejected when VRF IS fulfilled â€” must claim instead). Target: all tests green. Verify: `anchor test --skip-local-validator`.\n\n- [ ] [engine] Re-run `scripts/sync-idl` to update `packages/anchor-client/` with new coinflip IDL (new CoinflipMatch shape with RoundPhase + vrf_request_key, removed resolve_match instruction, updated claim_payout accounts to include Orao randomness). Verify: `anchor build && pnpm lint` in anchor-client package.\n\n- [ ] [docs] Drop all MagicBlock VRF references from codebase: update `sources/rng-utopia/CLAUDE.md` locked decisions table (MagicBlock â†’ Orao), remove MagicBlock comments from coinflip source files, clean up any remaining `ephemeral-vrf-sdk` references. Verify: `grep -r \"MagicBlock\\|ephemeral.vrf\" sources/rng-utopia/solana/ sources/rng-utopia/CLAUDE.md` returns zero matches.\n\n### Testing Requirements\n\nThe agent MUST complete ALL before outputting the completion signal:\n\n#### Code Quality\n- [ ] All existing tests pass\n- [ ] New tests added for each shared module\n- [ ] No lint errors\n\n#### Functional Verification\n- [ ] All acceptance criteria verified\n- [ ] Edge cases handled (zero amounts, expired deadlines, double-settle, paused state)\n- [ ] Error states handled (invalid transitions, commitment mismatch, insufficient funds)\n\n#### Console/Network Check\n- [ ] `anchor build` succeeds\n- [ ] `anchor test` passes all program tests\n\n### Iteration Instructions\n\nIf ANY check fails:\n1. Identify the specific issue\n2. Fix the code\n3. Re-run tests\n4. Re-verify all criteria\n5. Check again\n\n**Only when ALL checks pass, output:** `<promise>DONE</promise>`\n\n### Post-Completion: Gap Analysis\n\nAfter the spec loop outputs `<promise>DONE</promise>`, `spec-loop.sh` automatically runs\n`/gap-analysis {id} --non-interactive` which:\n1. Audits every FR acceptance criterion against the codebase\n2. Writes `docs/specs/004-shared-infrastructure/gap-analysis.md` with inventory + audit + recommendations\n3. Annotates FR checkboxes with HTML comment evidence (`<!-- satisfied: ... -->`)\n4. Commits everything together with the completion commit\n","numLines":297,"startLine":1,"totalLines":297}}}
